crfModuleGuideline: Summary of Recommendations for Physical Function
description: Individuals with TBI (particularly severe TBI) may manifest difficulties in physical or neurological functioning including cranial or peripheral nerve damage, impairment in motor functioning, strength and/or coordination, or impairment in sensation. These impairments may contribute to difficulties in performing day-to-day activities safely and independently.

crfModuleGuideline: Summary of Recommendations for Post-concussive/TBI-Related Symptoms
description: TBI-related symptoms include somatic (e.g., headaches, visual disturbances), cognitive (e.g., attention and memory difficulties) and emotional (e.g., irritability) symptoms. They are commonly reported after TBI or concussion and may persist in some cases at all levels of TBI severity.

crfModuleGuideline: Summary of Recommendations for Psychiatric and Psychological Status
description: Psychological issues associated with TBI that affect outcomes include adjustment problems, personality changes (e.g., impulsivity), or mood disturbances. In the context of pediatric TBI, psychological/psychiatric variables are behavioral and emotional constructs related to positive or negative functioning. In addition, substance use disorders (SUD) are prevalent among persons with TBI and can have a substantial impact on long-term outcomes. These variables may be premorbid or posttraumatic in occurrence. Etiologies are both biologic and environmental.

description: Duration of coma, level of consciousness and rate of memory recovery contribute significantly to functional outcome, and play a key role in treatment and disposition planning.

crfModuleGuideline: Summary of Recommendations for Social Cognition
description: Social cognition refers to the cognitive processes necessary for successful social interaction. A growing body of literature has documented impairments in this domain after TBI, in some cases independent of other cognitive impairments.

crfModuleGuideline: Summary of Recommendations for Social Role Participation and Social Competence
description: Participation is defined by the World Health Organization (WHO) as  involvement in life situations , and commonly includes engagement in endeavors within one's community. TBI affects many areas of participation including work/ productive activity, recreation and leisure pursuits, and social/ family role function.

cdes.cdeName: Surgical or therapeutic procedure ICD-9-CM code
cdes.definitionDescription: Code from the International Classification of Diseases, Ninth Revision, Clinical Modification (ICD-9-CM) for the selected surgical procedure
cdes.questionText: Surgical or therapeutic procedure ICD-9-CM code
cdes.instructions: Choose all that apply. Recommend collection during acute hospital care. Document information on a continuing basis and check/update on discharge/death from review of medical charts. Add date stamp for when assessed.  In previous trials and studies, information on surgical procedures has typically been documented in free text format, thus often precluding any meaningful analysis. We therefore propose the use of ICD-9 coding.

description: The symptoms included in the questionnaire are associated with sleep disorders such as sleep apnea-related symptoms, difficulty sleeping symptoms, EDS symptoms, and narcolepsy-like symptoms.

cdes.cdeName: Survey Screen for Sleep Apnea (SSSA) - loud snore frequency
cdes.definitionDescription: The frequency for how often the participant has snored loudly in the last month as part of the Survey Screen for Sleep Apnea (SSSA).
cdes.permissibleDescription: Never;Rarely (less than once a week);Sometimes (1-2 times per week);Frequently (3-4 times per week);Always (5-7 times per week);Do not know;
cdes.instructions: During the last month, on how many nights or days per week have you had or been told you had the following (please check only one box per question)
cdes.referrences: Maislin G, Pack AI, Kribbs NB, et al. A survey screen for prediction of apnea. Sleep 1995;18:158-166.  The Multivariable Apnea Prediction (MAP) Index and computing tools were developed by the Human Assessment and Biostatistics Core of the Center for Sleep and Respiratory Biology, University of Pennsylvania Medical Center. Research was supported the SCOR in Cardiopulmonary Disorders in Sleep (HL42236-08) and then by the SCOR for the Neurobiology of Sleep and Sleep Apnea (P50 HL-60287)

The date/time should be recorded to the level of granularity known (e.g., year, year and month, complete date plus hours and minutes, etc.).

cdes.cdeName: Headache history indicator
cdes.definitionDescription: Indicates whether participant/subject suffers from headaches
cdes.questionText: Does the participant/subject suffer from headaches?
cdes.instructions: If Yes, the participant/subject suffers from headaches, indicate the typical severity. If no, STOP.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Headache typical severity type
cdes.definitionDescription: The participant's/subject's typical headache pain severity
cdes.permissibleDescription: Most of the time I can ignore my headache and continue what I'm doing;My headache makes concentration difficult, but I can perform undemanding tasks;I cannot concentrate nor do much of anything;
cdes.instructions: Severity assessment in headache trials is most commonly collected as mild, moderate, severity; however pain severity is most commonly collected using an 11-point scale.  It’s unclear which of the two scales is more robust in differentiating active versus placebo or between two active treatments. We would recommend the use of both scales for future Preventive trials
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.permissibleValue: Able to work/function normally;Working ability or activity impaired to some degree;Working ability or activity severely impaired;Bed rest required;
cdes.permissibleDescription: Able to work/function normally;Working ability or activity impaired to some degree;Working ability or activity severely impaired;Bed rest required;
cdes.instructions: If participant/subject suffers from severe headaches, indicate what is affected.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined
cdes.previousTitle: Headache typical level activities affected type

cdes.cdeName: Headache typical pain intensity rating scale
cdes.definitionDescription: Rating scale for the pain of this headache on a scale of 0 -10
cdes.questionText: Rate your typical pain on a scale of 0-10
cdes.instructions: 0  = no pain &  10  = the worst pain Severity assessment in headache trials is most commonly collected as mild, moderate, severity; however pain severity is most commonly collected using an 10-point scale.  It's unclear which of the two scales is more robust in differentiating active versus placebo or between two active treatments. We would recommend the use of both scales for future Preventive trials.
cdes.referrences: Hershey AD, Powers S 2011.  Amitriptyline and Topiramate in the Prevention of Childhood Migraine Study.

cdes.cdeName: Tardieu Scale relative velocity rate
cdes.definitionDescription: The relative velocity (for a repeated measure) during administration of the Tardieu Scale assessment to measure muscle reaction through evaluation of spasticity and resistance to passive limb movement in a participant/subject.
cdes.permissibleDescription: V1 - As slow as possible, slower than the natural drop of the limb segment under gravity;V2 - Speed of limb segment falling under gravity;V3 - As fast as possible, faster than the rate of the natural drop of the limb segment under gravity;
cdes.instructions: Measurements take place at 3 velocities (V1, V2, and V3). Responses are recorded at each velocity as X/Y, with X indicating the 0 to 5 rating, and Y indicating the degree of angle at which the muscle reaction occurs.
cdes.referrences:
Key Reference:
Tardieu G, Shentoub S, Delarue R. (1954) Research on a technic for measurement of spasticity. Rev Neurol (Paris), 91(2): 143–144.
Other References:
Ansari, N. N., Naghdi, S., Hasson, S., Azarsa, M. H., & Azarnia, S. (2008). The Modified Tardieu Scale for the measurement of elbow flexor spasticity in adult patients with hemiplegia. Brain Inj, 22(13-14), 1007–1012. 
Boyd, R., & Graham, H. K. (1999). Objective measurement of clinical findings in the use of botulinum toxin type A for the management of children with CP. Eur J Neurol, 6(Suppol 4), S23–S35.
Gracies, J. M., Burke, K., Clegg, N. J., Browne, R., Rushing, C., Fehlings, D., . . . Delgado, M. R. (2010). Reliability of the Tardieu Scale for assessing spasticity in children with cerebral palsy. Arch Phys Med Rehabil, 91(3), 421–428.
Haugh AB, Pandyan AD, Johnson GR. (2006). A systematic review of the Tardieu Scale for the measurement of spasticity. Disabil Rehabil, 28(15): 899–907.
Morris, S. (2002). Ashworth And Tardieu Scales: Their Clinical Relevance For Measuring Spasticity In Adult And Paediatric Neurological Populations. Phys Ther Rev, 7(1), 53–62.

cdes.cdeName: Tardieu Scale movement resistance score
cdes.definitionDescription: The semi-quantitative score describing relative resistance to passive limb movement or occurrence of spasticity observed while administering the Tardieu Scale assessment to measure the reaction of muscles of a tested limb in a participant/subject.
cdes.permissibleDescription: No resistance throughout the course of the passive movement;Slight resistance throughout the course of passive movement, no clear catch at a precise angle;Clear catch at a precise angle, interrupting the passive movement, followed by release;Fatigable clonus with less than 10 seconds when maintaining the pressure and appearing at the precise angle;Unfatigable clonus with more than 10 seconds when maintaining the pressure and appearing at a precise angle;Joint is immovable (Indicate which assistive device the participant uses);
cdes.instructions: Measurements take place at 3 velocities (V1, V2, and V3). Responses are recorded at each velocity as X/Y, with X indicating the 0 to 5 rating, and Y indicating the degree of angle at which the muscle reaction occurs.

cdes.permissibleDescription: V1 - As slow as possible, slower than the natural drop of the limb segment under gravity;V2 - Speed of limb segment falling under gravity;V3 - As fast as possible, faster than the rate of the natural drop of the limb segment under gravity;
cdes.instructions: Measurements take place at 3 velocities (V1, V2, and V3). Responses are recorded at each velocity as X/Y, with X indicating the 0 to 5 rating, and Y indicating the degree of angle at which the muscle reaction occurs.
cdes.referrences:
Key Reference:
Tardieu G, Shentoub S, Delarue R. (1954) Research on a technic for measurement of spasticity. Rev Neurol (Paris), 91(2): 143–144.
Other References:
Ansari, N. N., Naghdi, S., Hasson, S., Azarsa, M. H., & Azarnia, S. (2008). The Modified Tardieu Scale for the measurement of elbow flexor spasticity in adult patients with hemiplegia. Brain Inj, 22(13-14), 1007–1012. 
Boyd, R., & Graham, H. K. (1999). Objective measurement of clinical findings in the use of botulinum toxin type A for the management of children with CP. Eur J Neurol, 6(Suppol 4), S23–S35.
Gracies, J. M., Burke, K., Clegg, N. J., Browne, R., Rushing, C., Fehlings, D., . . . Delgado, M. R. (2010). Reliability of the Tardieu Scale for assessing spasticity in children with cerebral palsy. Arch Phys Med Rehabil, 91(3), 421–428.
Haugh AB, Pandyan AD, Johnson GR. (2006). A systematic review of the Tardieu Scale for the measurement of spasticity. Disabil Rehabil, 28(15): 899–907.
Morris, S. (2002). Ashworth And Tardieu Scales: Their Clinical Relevance For Measuring Spasticity In Adult And Paediatric Neurological Populations. Phys Ther Rev, 7(1), 53–62.
cdes.aliasesForVariableName: Aliases for variable name not defined

cdes.cdeName: Tardieu Scale movement resistance score
cdes.definitionDescription: The semi-quantitative score describing relative resistance to passive limb movement or occurrence of spasticity observed while administering the Tardieu Scale assessment to measure the reaction of muscles of a tested limb in a participant/subject.
cdes.permissibleDescription: No resistance throughout the course of the passive movement;Slight resistance throughout the course of passive movement, no clear catch at a precise angle;Clear catch at a precise angle, interrupting the passive movement, followed by release;Fatigable clonus with less than 10 seconds when maintaining the pressure and appearing at the precise angle;Unfatigable clonus with more than 10 seconds when maintaining the pressure and appearing at a precise angle;Joint is immovable (Indicate which assistive device the participant uses);
cdes.instructions: Measurements take place at 3 velocities (V1, V2, and V3). Responses are recorded at each velocity as X/Y, with X indicating the 0 to 5 rating, and Y indicating the degree of angle at which the muscle reaction occurs.

cdes.cdeName: Tardieu Scale muscle reaction angle measurement
cdes.definitionDescription: The degree of angle for limb position at which muscle reaction or spasticity occurs for a given velocity administered during the Tardieu Scale assessment to measure the reaction of muscles of a tested limb in a participant/subject.
cdes.questionText: Y (Degree of angle at which muscle reaction occurs)
cdes.instructions: Measurements take place at 3 velocities (V1, V2, and V3). Responses are recorded at each velocity as X/Y, with X indicating the 0 to 5 rating, and Y indicating the degree of angle at which the muscle reaction occurs.
